WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.080
I am Brian Tarrant. I'm the editor of a website called Real World Data Science. And my talk

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:16.520
today is to tell you about how we built real world data science. This is a screenshot of

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:23.600
it here, how we built that using Quarto. And I guess some of my journey of discovery and

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:29.360
learning as I moved from being a journalist who knew pretty much nothing about any of

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:33.480
these tools to somebody who built a website, which I'm quite proud of. And I hope you'll

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:39.599
go and explore it. So I'm a journalist. That means I think a lot about words and the impact

00:00:39.599 --> 00:00:43.880
that they can have on people and how a few words, you know, strung together in a short

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:48.439
phrase can, you know, have a real impact on your life, make you think differently about

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:53.639
the world, change your perspective, whatever it might be. For example, will you marry me?

00:00:53.639 --> 00:00:57.240
Right? Someone says that to you, you're going to feel pretty good about yourself for a while,

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:00.959
right? A few years later, maybe things aren't going so well. When you hear those words,

00:01:00.959 --> 00:01:06.000
I want a divorce. I know, you know, that will knock you for six, right? Well, I had a kind

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.040
of experience like that that knocked me back a little bit recently when in March 2022,

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:17.000
my boss came to me and said, build us a website. Now, that isn't quite as dramatic as will

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:23.080
you marry me or I want a divorce, but it kind of knocked me back a little bit because the

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:27.480
background to this was I had applied for a job to build a new online publication for

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:35.040
my employer. I'd worked as a print journalist most of my career, but I'd worked on websites,

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:40.440
I'd done some design projects. I'd never built a website from the ground up, but I'd been

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:44.900
involved in things and, you know, I was feeling cocky. I knew a bit of HTML. I thought I'd

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:51.900
be fine. How difficult can it be to build a website? And then I started to think about

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:58.720
all the steps that I would need to go through in order to build the website. And I felt

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:05.720
like I maybe had bitten off more than I could chew. But that all changed when I started

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:13.039
speaking to some data scientists and someone said to me, do you know quarto? This four

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:19.080
word phrase, and it really changed my perspective on what's possible to do with digital publications

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:22.880
now. So I'll back up a little bit and tell you a bit about the context of where I was

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:27.240
coming from. So the challenge, I worked for the Royal Statistical Society. We're a membership

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:33.360
organisation for statisticians. We've been going for about 200 years. And our president

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:39.240
at the time felt that we needed to do more to support statisticians that are working

00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:43.559
as data scientists and also to contribute more to the data science conversation. Statisticians

00:02:43.559 --> 00:02:46.759
have a role to play in that and we didn't feel like we were doing as much as we could

00:02:46.759 --> 00:02:51.440
do. So we wanted to create a new publication for data science professionals, something

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:55.440
that would focus on real world examples of data science practice and that would generally

00:02:55.440 --> 00:03:01.360
kind of support knowledge sharing within the community. When I came into the project, I

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:04.479
was thinking I wanted to make sure that the website that we built would be a suitable

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:08.800
home for data scientists to contribute to because in my previous role, I was editing

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:14.679
a magazine, a statistics magazine called Significance. And I spent about eight years really annoying

00:03:14.679 --> 00:03:19.960
contributors because they would present these lovingly crafted late tech articles and they'd

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:23.960
send them to me and I'd say, excellent, thank you very much, could you redo that in Word?

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:28.119
And often that was followed by a deep sigh. So I thought, right, if we're going to do

00:03:28.119 --> 00:03:31.119
this, we're going to build something new. We want to build something that uses tools

00:03:31.119 --> 00:03:38.080
that data scientists use and that, you know, it's kind of speaking your language, essentially.

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:44.240
So I started phoning around, speaking to people I know, and that's when I heard that phrase,

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:48.279
do you know quarto? And the first time I heard it, I just jotted it down in my notebook.

00:03:48.279 --> 00:03:53.080
I think I misspelt it, but it was the second time that this came up. Another person I was

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:56.520
speaking to, somebody else said, do you know quarto? And I thought, I probably should look

00:03:56.520 --> 00:04:01.839
into this. So I went across to the website. This is what it looks like sort of now. It

00:04:01.839 --> 00:04:07.119
was broadly the same back when I started looking at it. And this really intrigued me straight

00:04:07.119 --> 00:04:10.440
away because, you know, even with my sort of very rudimentary knowledge, I knew that

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:14.119
on the left was like the core, the raw underlying code, if you like, and that was generating

00:04:14.119 --> 00:04:17.839
the outputs on the right. I liked the outputs on the right. I thought they looked nice and

00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:24.359
clean and crisp, and they had a kind of just a simplicity that I would like in a kind of

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:29.399
online publication. I also liked the fact that the, I could see that the figures were

00:04:29.399 --> 00:04:33.119
being generated from the code. I'd spent a lot of time, again, annoying contributors

00:04:33.119 --> 00:04:37.440
to Significance Magazine by telling them that they hadn't output in the right resolution

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:41.239
or the right size or whatever it might be. So this could kind of deal with all those

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:47.160
sorts of problems. So I thought, great, I'm going to learn quarto and also borrow that

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:56.760
guy's shirt. So I couldn't copy the hairstyle, unfortunately. So step one, went to the quarto

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:01.480
website. Easy, right? Download. I've downloaded lots of things in the past on my PC. Not a

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:04.920
problem. This is where things started to get difficult for me. I know what a text editor

00:05:04.920 --> 00:05:12.200
is. I have, I recognized RStudio and Jupyter. I think I once accessed a Jupyter notebook

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:15.760
and accidentally collapsed all the text chunks and code cells, and I didn't know what I was

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:20.559
doing and got out of there pretty quick. So clearly I needed to learn more than just

00:05:20.559 --> 00:05:24.600
quarto. I needed to learn a tool as well. I picked Visual Studio Code because it was

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:30.640
first on the list. So two things now, learn quarto, learn Visual Studio Code. Okay, fine.

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:35.040
Well, anyway, fortunately, quarto has made this easy because there's a whole load of

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:40.720
tutorials on the site, obviously starting with helping me to get familiar with working

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:46.040
with a quarto document and then transitioning over to looking at how to build a website.

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:54.040
So I think maybe it took me several days to a week, and I built my first website. A little

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:58.480
demo. It's not the world's best website, but it was my first website, and I felt proud

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:03.760
of it. You could see that, you know, I'd started to play around with how we might position,

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:07.079
you know, different sort of content blocks and things like that. But there was more work

00:06:07.079 --> 00:06:11.600
that needed to be done, not least the fact that this was on my local machine, and a website's

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:16.679
only really good if it's actually on the internet so everybody can see it. So I went back to

00:06:16.679 --> 00:06:20.480
the quarto guide, and then I found this thing about GitHub Pages, right? So I'd been using

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:26.399
GitHub mostly as a file, like a kind of personal file storage. I didn't really understand it,

00:06:26.399 --> 00:06:31.119
but I was familiar with the word, so I figured GitHub Pages would be the way to go for this.

00:06:31.119 --> 00:06:35.079
GitHub Action, this sounded exciting. Automatically render your files. Didn't want to have to

00:06:35.079 --> 00:06:40.200
be doing that manually every time, so I thought I would try this. But I quickly realized looking

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:45.239
at a few GitHub Actions that I had no idea what I was doing, and I had no idea how these

00:06:45.239 --> 00:06:51.559
things worked. So now I was learning Quarto, learning Visual Studio Code, and GitHub as

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:59.640
well. I have made a huge mistake. I really thought that that was it. But I then discovered

00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:03.799
the section on the Quarto website, which was the gallery, and then this little subsection

00:07:03.799 --> 00:07:11.320
here about websites. These three websites in particular, the NASA and OpenScape sites,

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:16.720
Amine's data science in a box, and along with the Quarto website, these were really helpful

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:22.119
to me because as well as looking at the websites, I could go onto their GitHub repos and look

00:07:22.119 --> 00:07:28.239
at how the sites were built. I could interrogate the actions and see broadly how these things

00:07:28.239 --> 00:07:33.359
were working and try and figure it out slowly in my head. I mean, the actions I'd built

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:38.079
failed multiple times, but eventually I got somewhere. I got somewhere with it.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:46.320
And as I was digging around in these repos, I realized something that I guess I didn't know

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:51.760
about GitHub before, which is that it's not just a personal storage for files. It's a platform

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:56.559
for collaboration and co-creation. I don't have a software or engineering background or anything

00:07:56.559 --> 00:08:01.839
like that, so I never would have had to use it for that reason. But the fact that I could see

00:08:01.839 --> 00:08:07.760
in each of these repos people working together, collaborating on projects, sharing ideas,

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:12.399
solving problems, this really changed my whole perspective about how we could build our website.

00:08:12.399 --> 00:08:16.160
So I was thinking about it in a kind of old media sense before, which is we'll build a website,

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:20.720
people will come to us and submit articles, and we'll publish them. But I actually thought,

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:25.359
well, maybe we could actually create this website together as a community, that it isn't just

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:30.399
something that we build and maintain. It's something that everybody can feel involved

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:38.159
in and can contribute to. I wanted to make sure that if you wanted to share your expertise,

00:08:39.119 --> 00:08:42.799
but your expertise or your passion wasn't necessarily writing articles about data science

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:46.719
projects you work on, maybe you could contribute to the maintenance of the site. Maybe you've

00:08:46.719 --> 00:08:51.280
seen a really cool thing in Quarto that you think we should add to our site, and you could help us

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:55.280
do that. Maybe there's something we could, an extension or whatever, that we could build and

00:08:55.280 --> 00:09:01.200
share with the wider community. And when I went back to my priorities or the challenge that

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:06.479
was set for me, I realized that this idea here about creating a support community around

00:09:07.039 --> 00:09:11.119
what we wanted to build was already in there. It took this process for me to,

00:09:12.239 --> 00:09:18.559
I guess, for it to be highlighted to me and to draw it out. So if you go to the site now,

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:24.719
you'll see that we are up and running. We have people who are contributing to the front end.

00:09:24.719 --> 00:09:30.479
They're sharing case studies. They are putting together tutorials and explainers about data

00:09:30.479 --> 00:09:35.760
science tools and methods. They're sharing the stories of their careers and how they got into

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:42.479
data science, what they've learned, and giving advice to people who are looking to follow in

00:09:42.479 --> 00:09:49.440
their footsteps. And we've also created a space for people to talk about the perspectives and

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:55.599
big themes and challenges in data science. But the other thing that started to happen,

00:09:55.599 --> 00:09:58.880
and this has happened organically, is that people have started to think about,

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:03.599
as I was saying, supporting the website beyond just creating content for it. So

00:10:04.479 --> 00:10:09.679
about a month ago now, a data science student in the Netherlands, Finn Ole Hoene, got in touch

00:10:09.679 --> 00:10:14.880
with us and said, you know, I'd like to build a template for real-world data science so that if

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:19.679
people want to write for you, there's a kind of example quarto document in there which shows all

00:10:19.679 --> 00:10:24.320
the different code features that you can use with the article. And when they render it, it will look

00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:27.760
like it will look on your website. And I think that's really important. If you're thinking about

00:10:28.479 --> 00:10:32.880
contributing to a publication, thinking about how you're going to design and set out your content,

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:38.159
being able to see what the finished product is going to look like is key. And this really

00:10:38.159 --> 00:10:42.799
warmed my heart that Finn took this step to do this, because it's something I wanted to do,

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:47.840
but I didn't have the kind of know-how to do it. I knew we needed a template of some sort,

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:51.679
but I didn't know how to build it. So Finn stepped up and helped us to create it. So that's,

00:10:52.239 --> 00:10:58.799
I think, showing the strength of the community. So these are just a sample of the people that

00:10:58.799 --> 00:11:03.280
have contributed to the site so far. These are only the contributors who have GitHub accounts.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:07.359
There are people that are kind of contributing through different avenues. But now we're starting

00:11:07.359 --> 00:11:10.960
to see not just people creating content, but people like Finn and Zoe, who I've highlighted,

00:11:11.039 --> 00:11:14.320
who are helping us sort of work through the science bugs and all that sort of stuff.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:21.840
I feel like I'm learning a lot from working with this community. And it's been really beneficial.

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:28.880
One of the things that I pointed out when I first went to the Quarto site was that there's this live

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:33.039
rendering of figures from the document. Well, we quickly figured out with some work that this was

00:11:33.039 --> 00:11:36.719
going to kill our website rendering speed, so we couldn't use that. So the community helped us to

00:11:36.719 --> 00:11:41.679
figure out a way around that, where we could still output the figures, but drop them into the

00:11:41.679 --> 00:11:47.760
article as image files instead. Code annotation. This is a cool new feature that's in Quarto.

