Clearly, I wasn't reading the updates diligently enough, because Finn had to point this out to me

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:56.960
that this was a thing, right, that you could build. And it's a really interactive, tactile way

00:11:56.960 --> 00:12:01.679
for people to kind of understand what's going on in your code. And I also learned that designing

00:12:01.679 --> 00:12:08.559
for HTML was a lot harder than it first appeared. We got a design company to kind of come up with

00:12:08.559 --> 00:12:13.119
the brand and the look of the website for us, but they literally just dropped a load of

00:12:13.119 --> 00:12:20.000
in-design documents off and said, you go and implement that now. So I had to figure out CSS

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.799
pretty quickly. And I did that by, again, going to look at other people's websites, seeing what

00:12:24.799 --> 00:12:30.640
they've done, and then trying to adapt it for our own purposes. And because I feel like I've learned

00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:34.479
so much from the community, I'm also trying to sort of give back and share what I've learned,

